# Microbiome–Metabolome Multi-omics Integration for IBD Candidate Biomarker Discovery

This project performs a reproducible secondary analysis of public IBDMDB/HMP2 multi-omics data to identify exploratory microbiome–metabolome candidate biomarker signatures associated with inflammatory bowel disease (IBD) disease state.

The analysis focuses on paired stool metagenomic taxonomic profiles, stool metabolomics profiles, and phenotype metadata. The goal is not to build a clinically validated diagnostic model, but to construct a clean matched multi-omics cohort and nominate candidate taxa–metabolite signatures supported by multiple lines of evidence.

## Research question

Can paired gut microbial taxa and stool metabolite profiles identify exploratory candidate biomarker signatures associated with IBD diagnosis?

The main comparisons are:

- IBD vs non-IBD
- Crohn's disease (CD) vs non-IBD
- ulcerative colitis (UC) vs non-IBD
- CD vs UC

## Dataset

This project uses public processed data products from the IBDMDB/HMP2 resource.

The analysis uses three data layers:

1. phenotype/sample metadata
2. metagenomic taxonomic profiles
3. stool metabolomics profiles

Raw FASTQ files, raw LC-MS files, metatranscriptomics, proteomics, host transcriptomics, and virome data were not included. The project is intentionally focused on a reproducible processed-data workflow.

Large raw/public source files are not stored in this repository because of file size. The scripts document how data were obtained, parsed, matched, and processed.

## Final cohort

The workflow started from 2,892 metadata samples. After matching metadata, microbiome, and metabolomics data, the final paired multi-omics cohort retained:

| Analysis set | Samples | Participants |
|---|---:|---:|
| Longitudinal matched set | 388 | 105 |
| Primary independent set | 105 | 105 |

The primary independent set keeps one matched stool sample per participant and was used for supervised integration and final candidate ranking to reduce repeated-measure leakage.

Disease group distribution in the primary independent set:

| Diagnosis | Samples | Participants |
|---|---:|---:|
| CD | 49 | 49 |
| UC | 30 | 30 |
| non-IBD | 26 | 26 |

## Analysis workflow

The project follows this workflow:

```text
public processed IBDMDB/HMP2 data
        |
        v
metadata, microbiome, and metabolomics parsing
        |
        v
sample identifier cleaning and multi-omics matching
        |
        v
primary independent set + longitudinal matched set
        |
        v
microbiome preprocessing
  - remove unknown/unclassified taxa
  - prevalence filtering
  - mean abundance filtering
  - pseudocount
  - CLR transformation
        |
        v
metabolomics preprocessing
  - missingness filtering
  - half-minimum imputation
  - log2 transformation
  - z-score scaling
  - near-zero variance filtering
        |
        v
single-omics analysis
  - alpha diversity
  - Bray-Curtis and Aitchison ordination
  - PERMANOVA
  - beta-dispersion check
  - MaAsLin2-style taxa association
  - metabolite association models
        |
        v
cross-omics integration
  - taxa-metabolite Spearman correlation
  - FDR correction
  - mixOmics/sPLS exploratory feature selection
        |
        v
multi-evidence candidate biomarker ranking
        |
        v
Quarto report and final figures/tables
```

## Key methods

### Microbiome analysis

Genus-level taxonomic profiles were filtered and transformed using centered log-ratio (CLR) transformation. This was done because microbiome relative abundance data are compositional.

Community-level structure was assessed using:

- Shannon diversity
- observed richness
- Bray-Curtis PCoA
- Aitchison PCA
- PERMANOVA
- beta-dispersion testing

### Metabolomics analysis

Metabolite features were filtered and processed using:

- missingness filtering
- half-minimum imputation
- log2 transformation
- z-score scaling
- near-zero variance filtering

Most top-ranked metabolite features could not be mapped to confirmed metabolite names, so they are reported conservatively as unannotated LC-MS metabolite features.

### Disease association models

Genus-level taxa and metabolite features were tested across disease comparisons. Multiple testing correction was performed using Benjamini-Hochberg FDR.

### Cross-omics integration

Cross-omics analysis was restricted to selected disease-associated or top-ranked features instead of all possible taxa-metabolite combinations.

The integration included:

- Spearman correlation between genus-level CLR abundance and scaled metabolite abundance
- FDR correction across taxa-metabolite pairs
- exploratory mixOmics/sPLS feature selection
- final multi-evidence candidate ranking

The sPLS model was used for exploratory feature selection only. It should not be interpreted as a clinically validated classifier.

## Main results

### 1. A clean paired multi-omics cohort was constructed

After sample matching, 388 longitudinal matched samples from 105 participants were retained. A primary independent analysis set of 105 samples was created by keeping one matched sample per participant.

This step is a core part of the project because it avoids treating repeated samples as independent observations in downstream supervised analysis.

### 2. Alpha diversity did not significantly differ by diagnosis

Alpha diversity testing showed no significant diagnosis-level difference:

| Metric | Test | Statistic | p-value | q-value |
|---|---|---:|---:|---:|
| Shannon diversity | Kruskal-Wallis | 3.28 | 0.194 | 0.194 |
| Observed richness | Kruskal-Wallis | 3.84 | 0.146 | 0.194 |

This suggests that broad within-sample diversity was not the strongest disease-associated microbiome signal in the matched subset.

### 3. Aitchison ordination showed detectable diagnosis-associated microbiome structure

PERMANOVA results suggested small but detectable diagnosis-associated community structure:

| Distance | R² | F | p-value |
|---|---:|---:|---:|
| Bray-Curtis | 0.0314 | 1.65 | 0.051 |
| Aitchison | 0.0362 | 1.91 | 0.003 |

Beta-dispersion tests were not significant:

| Distance | p-value |
|---|---:|
| Bray-Curtis | 0.967 |
| Aitchison | 0.243 |

This supports the interpretation that diagnosis-associated microbiome structure was present, although the effect size was small.

### 4. Genus-level taxa did not survive FDR correction

The genus-level taxa analysis tested 39 filtered genera across four disease comparisons, producing 156 association results.

No genus-level taxa survived FDR correction.

This negative result was retained and reported directly. The microbiome signal was therefore interpreted as community-level and integration-level evidence rather than strong single-genus biomarker evidence.

### 5. Metabolite features showed stronger disease-associated signal

The metabolomics analysis tested 40,306 metabolite features across four disease comparisons, producing 161,224 association results.

A total of 1,730 metabolite association results survived FDR correction.

Significant metabolite results by comparison:

| Comparison | FDR-significant results |
|---|---:|
| UC vs non-IBD | 1,094 |
| IBD vs non-IBD | 442 |
| CD vs non-IBD | 110 |
| CD vs UC | 84 |

The strongest metabolite signal was observed in UC vs non-IBD comparisons.

### 6. Cross-omics correlation identified significant taxa-metabolite pairs

Spearman correlation analysis identified 230 significant taxa-metabolite pairs after FDR correction.

Top examples included:

| Taxon | Metabolite feature | Spearman rho | FDR |
|---|---|---:|---:|
| Ruminococcus | C8p_QI7970 | -0.490 | 0.000452 |
| Clostridium | C18n_QI4874 | 0.464 | 0.000587 |
| Eggerthella | C18n_QI4874 | 0.463 | 0.000587 |
| Coprobacillus | C18n_QI4874 | 0.462 | 0.000587 |
| Anaerotruncus | HILn_QI25565 | 0.459 | 0.000587 |
| Ruminococcus | C8p_QI10300 | -0.458 | 0.000587 |

These results connect the microbiome and metabolome layers and provide candidate paired signatures rather than isolated single-omics markers.

### 7. mixOmics/sPLS selected recurrent microbial and metabolite features

The exploratory sPLS model used:

| Item | Value |
|---|---:|
| Samples | 105 |
| Components | 2 |
| Microbiome features input | 39 |
| Metabolite features input | 100 |
| Apparent training-set accuracy | 0.733 |

The apparent accuracy is reported only as a descriptive training-set metric. It is not external validation.

Selected microbial features included:

- Ruminococcus
- Anaerotruncus
- Odoribacter
- Bilophila
- Roseburia
- Dorea
- Faecalibacterium
- Clostridium
- Coprobacillus
- Akkermansia
- Eubacterium

Selected metabolite features included:

- C18n_QI11343
- C18n_QI4641
- C18n_QI2917
- C18n_QI8008
- C18n_QI8815
- HILp_QI2095
- HILp_QI2044
- C18n_QI7605
- C18n_QI7515
- C8p_QI7970
- C8p_QI10300

### 8. Final candidate biomarker ranking prioritised multi-evidence pairs

The final ranking produced 230 exploratory candidate taxa-metabolite pairs.

Top candidate pairs included:

| Rank | Taxon | Metabolite feature | Metabolite FDR | Spearman rho | Correlation FDR | sPLS loading | Overall score |
|---:|---|---|---:|---:|---:|---:|---:|
| 1 | Ruminococcus | C8p_QI7970 | 0.00198 | -0.490 | 0.000452 | 0.840 | 0.634 |
| 2 | Ruminococcus | C8p_QI10300 | 0.00167 | -0.458 | 0.000587 | 0.840 | 0.582 |
| 3 | Faecalibacterium | C18n_QI7605 | 0.0000105 | 0.322 | 0.0219 | 0.140 | 0.582 |
| 4 | Ruminococcus | C8p_QI21618 | 0.000824 | -0.408 | 0.00311 | 0.840 | 0.572 |
| 5 | Faecalibacterium | HILp_QI2044 | 0.000386 | 0.412 | 0.00264 | 0.164 | 0.568 |

The top-ranked pair, Ruminococcus-C8p_QI7970, was supported by metabolite disease association, cross-omics correlation, and sPLS selection.

Because the metabolite feature is not confidently annotated, it should be reported as an exploratory taxon-LC-MS feature signature rather than a named metabolite biomarker.

