## Reproducibility

This project uses R, Quarto, and `renv`.

To reproduce the analysis:

```r
renv::restore()
```

Then run the scripts in order:

```r
source("R/01_download_data.R")
source("R/02_parse_tables.R")
source("R/03_match_samples_qc.R")
source("R/04_microbiome_preprocessing.R")
source("R/05_metabolome_preprocessing.R")
source("R/06_diversity_ordination.R")
source("R/07_differential_abundance_maaslin2.R")
source("R/08_metabolite_association_models.R")
source("R/09_cross_omics_correlations.R")
source("R/10_spls_mixomics_integration.R")
source("R/11_biomarker_ranking.R")
source("R/12_make_figures_tables.R")
```

Render the report:

```r
quarto::quarto_render("analysis_report.qmd")
```

## Interpretation boundaries

This project should be interpreted carefully.

What this project supports:

- a clean matched public multi-omics analysis workflow
- microbiome community-level disease-associated structure
- stronger metabolite-level disease-associated signal
- exploratory taxa-metabolite candidate signatures
- reproducible candidate ranking for follow-up

What this project does not claim:

- clinical diagnostic biomarkers
- causal microbiome-metabolite mechanisms
- externally validated prediction performance
- confirmed metabolite identities for unannotated LC-MS features
- raw sequencing or raw LC-MS reprocessing

## Skills demonstrated

This project demonstrates:

- R programming
- tidyverse data wrangling
- public multi-omics data handling
- metadata cleaning and sample matching
- microbiome compositional data analysis
- CLR transformation
- Aitchison ordination
- PERMANOVA and beta-dispersion testing
- metabolomics preprocessing
- missingness filtering and imputation
- feature-wise disease association modelling
- MaAsLin2-style multivariable association analysis
- FDR correction
- taxa-metabolite Spearman correlation
- mixOmics/sPLS exploratory feature selection
- multi-evidence biomarker ranking
- Quarto reporting
- GitHub-oriented reproducible project organisation

